05543nam a22007935i 9781501715143DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20182018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018025891  a97815017151437 a10.7591/97815017151432doi  a(DE-B1597)503493  a(OCoLC)1039436389  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aE175.5.B38 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a973.07202aB2231 aDrake, Richard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCharles Austin Beard :bThe Return of the Master Historian of American Imperialism /cRichard Drake. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Beardian Interpretation of American History -- t1. Discovering the Economic Taproot of Imperialism -- t2. Two Contrasting Progressive Views of the Great War -- t3. Becoming a Revisionist -- t4. Washington and Wall Street Working Together for War -- t5. Isolationism versus Internationalism -- t6. A Wartime Trilogy -- t7. Waging War for the Four Freedoms -- t8. Beard Finds an Ally in Herbert Hoover -- t9. Attacking “the Saint” -- t10. Defending Beard after the Fall -- t11. Beard’s Philosophy of History and American Imperialism -- tConclusion: The Sad Historian of the Pensive Plain -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRichard Drake presents a new interpretation of Charles Austin Beard’s life and work. The foremost American historian and a leading public intellectual in the first half of the twentieth century, Beard participated actively in the debates about American politics and foreign policy surrounding the two world wars. Drake takes this famous man’s life and rewrites his intellectual biography by placing the European dimension of Beard’s thought at the center. This radical change of critical focus allows Drake to correct previous biographers’ oversights and, in Charles Austin Beard, present a far more nuanced appreciation for Beard’s life than we have read before.Drake proposes a restoration of Beard’s professional reputation, which he lost in large part because of his extremely unpopular opposition to America’s intervention in World War II. Drake analyzes the stages of Beard’s development as a historian and critic: his role as an intellectual leader in the Progressive movement, the support that he gave to the cause of American intervention in World War I, and his subsequent revisionist repudiation of Wilsonian ideals and embrace of non-interventionism in the lead-up to World War II. Many of his dire predictions about the inevitable consequences of pre-World War II American foreign policy have come to pass. Drake shows that, as Americans tally the ruinous costs--both financial and moral—of nation-building and informal empire, the life and work of this prophet of history merit a thorough reexamination.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aHistorianszUnited StatesvBiography. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aU.S. History. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aImperialism, Charles Austin Beard, restoration of Beard’s professional reputation, World War II, Progressive movement, Wilsonian ideals, embrace of non-interventionism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060655308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2018 Englishz978311060403008iT